{{other uses|Black Lion (disambiguation){{!}}Black Lion}}
The '''Black Lions''' were a [[anti-fascist]] [[resistance movement]]<ref>{{cite book|first=Bahru |last=Zewde |title=A History of Modern Ethiopia 1855-1991 |publisher=Addis Ababa University Press |year=2001|location=Addis Ababa |isbn= 0-8214-1440-2 |pages=168 }}</ref> formed to fight against [[Kingdom of Italy (1861-1946)|Italy]] during the [[Italian East Africa|occupation]] of the [[Ethiopian Empire]] in the [[Second World War]].<ref>{{cite book|authors=Shinn, David Hamilton & Ofcansky, Thomas P. & Prouty, Chris |title=Historical Dictionary of Ethiopia |publisher=Scarecrow Press|year=2004|location=Lanham, Maryland|isbn= 0-8108-4910-0 |pages=75 }}</ref><ref> {{cite book| authors=Selassie, Haile I & Marcus, Harold (Editor) & Gebions, Ezekiel (Translator)| title=My Life and Ethiopia's Progress: The Autobiography of Emperor Haile Selassie I, King of Kings and Lord of Lords|volume= II | publisher=Research Associates School Times Publications | year=1999 |location=Chicago |isbn= 0-948390-40-9 |pages=80 }}</ref>
As Bahru Zewde notes, in spite of its "marginal impact on the Resistance" the Black Lions made "eloquent attempts to give the struggle coherent ideological and political direction."<ref>Bahru Zewde, ''A History of Modern Ethiopia'', second edition (Oxford: James Currey, 2001), p. 174.</ref>
==History== The movement was founded in western Ethiopia, and included fighters such as the [[Shewa|Shoan]] ''[[Ras (title)|Ras]]'' [[Abebe Aregai]],{{fact|date=January 2011}} and a number of intellectuals who included the sons of Hakim [[Workneh Eshete]] and [[Heruy Welde Sellase]], and [[Yilma Deressa]].<ref>Bahru Zewde, ''Pioneers of Change in Ethiopia'' (Oxford: James Currey, 2002), p. 203</ref> Its chairman was [[Alemework Beyene]], a veterinary surgeon educated in Britain. The organization had a constitution consisting of ten points, which included: asserting the supremacy of the political sphere over the military, injunctions against mistreating peasants and prisoners of war, forbidding its members from seeking exile and urging them to prefer death to capture by the enemy.<ref>Bahru Zewde, ''A History'', p. 175</ref>
The group was effectively disbanded following the surrender of the ''Ras'' [[Imru Haile Selassie]] 18 December 1936.<ref>Anthony Mockler, ''Haile Selassie's War'' (New York: Olive Branch, 2003), pp. 168</ref> The majority of its members were killed by the Italians following the unsuccessful attempt on [[Rodolfo Graziani]]'s life on [[Yekatit 12|19 February 1937]].<ref>Bahru Zewde, ''Pioneers'', p. 204</ref> The few survivors included Alemework and Yilma.
==Details== The Black Lions dominated the early resistance movement in Ethiopia. Members of the Black Lions included students from the [[Oletta Military Academy]] and foreign-educated Ethiopians. The military academy was founded in 1935 and is located in [[Holeta Genet]].
The Black Lions convinced ''[[Ethiopian aristocratic and court titles|Ras]]''{{#tag:ref|Roughly equivalent to [[Duke]].|group=nb}} [[Imru Haile Selassie]] to join them in the armed struggle since he was part of the dynamics that created the movement. ''Ras'' Imru was appointed by [[Emperor of Ethiopia|Emperor]] [[Haile Selassie]] as [[Prince Regent]] in his absence. ''Ras'' Imru was to reorganize and continue to resist the Italians. To do this, he fell back to [[Gore, Ethiopia|Gore]] in southern Ethiopia. On 19 December 1936, after the Italians pinned him down on the north bank of the [[Gojeb River]], ''Ras'' Imru surrendered. The Black Lions organization then collapsed, and many of its members were liquidated.<ref>{{cite book|authors=Shinn, David Hamilton & Ofcansky, Thomas P. & Prouty, Chris |date=2004|title= Historical Dictionary of Ethiopia|location= Lanham, Maryland|publisher= Scarecrow Press|page=75|isbn=0-8108-4910-0}}</ref>
